🔹 Overview

This lab simulates a small enterprise environment for testing adversary techniques aligned with the MITRE ATT&CK framework. It is designed to replicate both attacker and defender perspectives within an isolated virtual network, enabling realistic attack simulation and detection engineering.

🔹 Lab Components

Attacker Machine

Kali Linux
Tools: CrackMapExec, Nmap, Impacket
Role: Executes reconnaissance, exploitation, and lateral movement

Workstation (Victim)

Windows 10
Domain-joined endpoint
Role: Initial access target and pivot point

Domain Controller

Windows Server 2022
Services: Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS), DNS
Role: Centralized authentication and identity management

Monitoring / SIEM

Splunk running on Ubuntu Server
Role: Log aggregation, detection, and analysis

Logging & Telemetry

Sysmon
Provides detailed endpoint telemetry (process creation, network connections, etc.)
Splunk Universal Forwarder
Installed on Windows endpoints to forward logs to Splunk

🔹 Network Architecture
All systems are hosted in a virtualized environment (e.g., VirtualBox or VMware)
Connected through an isolated internal network to prevent external exposure

Example IP Scheme:

Kali Linux: 192.168.56.10
Windows 10: 192.168.56.20
Domain Controller: 192.168.56.30
Splunk Server: 192.168.56.40
The Windows 10 workstation is joined to the Active Directory domain managed by the Domain Controller

🔹 Data Flow & Logging Pipeline
Attacks are launched from Kali Linux against Windows systems
Sysmon and Windows Event Logs generate detailed telemetry
Splunk Universal Forwarder collects and forwards logs
Logs are sent to the Splunk server on Ubuntu
Splunk indexes and analyzes the data for detection

🔹 Security Monitoring Objective
Simulate real-world attack techniques (credential access, lateral movement, etc.)
Capture high-fidelity telemetry using Sysmon
Detect and analyze malicious behavior using Splunk queries
Map observed activity to MITRE ATT&CK techniques
